  Attack Path (Docker Socket Escape)

  1. Discovered network access was allowed via the nono cap file
  2. Enumerated listening services with ss -tlnp
  3. Found Docker socket at /run/docker.sock — accessible because /run was allowed for read
  4. Queried Docker API via curl --unix-socket — daemon runs as root outside all Landlock restrictions
  5. Created a container with debian:trixie image, bind-mounting /var/log from the host
  6. Started container, read stdout logs — flag retrieved

  Key Vulnerability

  The nono sandbox allowed read access to /run (for /var/run compatibility), which exposed the Docker socket. Since the user (UID 1000) is in the docker group (or the socket permissions allow access), the Docker daemon — running as root with no Landlock restrictions — could be used
  to read any file on the host filesystem.

